avas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Jose, Jorge, Julio, Manuel, Roberto, Armando, Arturo, Alejandro, Carlos, Enrique, Francisco.","Asturian-Leonese and Spanish: plural form of   Nava  .","In some cases possibly Catalan (<b>Navàs</b>): habitational name from Navars in Barcelona province, Catalonia (Spain), denoting a place where people from Navarre lived."]},{"name":"Navar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Joaquin, Jose, Raul, Alfredo, Arturo, Erasmo, Ezequiel, Gilberto, Juan, Manuel, Miguel.","Spanish: probably a topographic name from a collective form of<i>nava</i> ‘treeless plateau’ (see   Nava  )."]}]},{"name":"Ordoño","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Philippines; <b>Ordoña</b>): altered form of Basque <b>Orduña</b> (see   Orduna  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Orduna","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Juan, Ruben, Jose, Alberto, Rafael, Andres, Felipe, Pilar, Alfonso, Alfredo, Alicia, Anastacia.","Basque (mainly <b>Orduña</b>): Castilianized form of a habitational name from Urduña (in Castilian: Orduña), a town in Biscay, Basque Country (Spain), Basque Country, Spain (in an exclave of Biscay, located between Araba/Álava and Burgos provinces)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ordoño Alvarez de las Asturias y Nava was born in 1150, his father, Alvaro Rodríguez de las Asturias Nava y Noroña, was 30 and his mother, Elvira Pérez de Azagra, was -1. He had at least 4 sons and 4 daughters with Elvira García De Braganza."},"et":{"hacia 1150–":"1150–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1206–1261":"1206–1261","1225–1280":"1225–1280","–1251":"–1251","–Male":"Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","aproximadam